{"title_page": "Yogeshwar Amatya", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{notability|biography|date=February 2015}}\n{{peacock|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Yogeshwar Amatya\n| image               =\n| caption             = Yogeshwar Amatya in Melancholy Song Recording at Radio Nepal Studio in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya\n| birth_place         = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| genre               = [[Soft rock]], [[pop rock]], [[folk music|folk]]\n| instrument          = Vocals guitar\n| occupation          = Singer<br> [[Composer]]<br>businessman<br> philanthropist\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Single Records|Single]] (Nepal)\n}}\n\n'''Yogeshwar Amatya''' (born Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya, 3 April) is a Nepali singer, musician, producer, actor, social activist, and photographer. Amatya has been a figure in Nepalese [[soft rock]] during the last two decades. He has sold more than 1 million records, making him one of [[List of best-selling music artists|Nepal's best-selling music artists]] and the best-selling [[Nepali rock]] artist of all time.\n\nAmatya came to fame in Nepal with his album ''Jaba Sandhya Hunchha'' and became more famous with his 1998 song ''Karai Kara Le''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nepalipopartist.blogspot.com/2007/10/yogeshwor-amatya.html | author = Thisaway | title = Profile of Nepali pop music artist..........: Yogeshwar Amatya | accessdate = 18 September 2010 | authorlink = Thisaway }}</ref> In 1998, he released his ''Ahile Chaahin Drabya Ko Aaasha Ma, Bastoo'' album which included ''Wakka Dikka''. Amatya also participated in [[Melancholy (song)|Melancholy]] song as a solo artist with 365 other Nepali singers and musician. The song set a [[Guinness World Record]] entitled \"Most Vocal Solos in a Song Recording\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-vocal-solos-in-a-song-recording|title=Most vocal solos in a song recording|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-05-29/nepali-house-hold-names-go-for-the-guinness-world-records.html|title=Nepali house-hold names go for the Guinness World Records|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/26897/|title=National poet Madhav Prasad Ghimire turns singer|first=Shreedhar|last=Pandey|website=My Republica|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAmatya has mentioned that he has never received any formal training in music. He says, \"I never had any formal training regarding music... I guess I have to say that I don't have any musical background, except late night jamming with tons of beer with my buddies.\"<ref name=Telg3672213>{{cite news|url=http://www.interview.bagaicha.com/Yogeshwar-Amatya-71.html#sthash.15OZFMba.dpuf|title=Interview with Yogeshwar Amatya |author=keran limbu|publisher=bagaicha.com|date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=1 July 2011|location=Nepal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAmatya hasn't used his [[middle name]] since his father dropped it. His father, Bhuwaneshor Amatya, was the first President of Nepal Chalchitra Sangha. His mother, Lamu Amatya, was the first trained nurse in Nepal.\n\nHe was bullied by classmates while studying at [[St. Xavier's College, Kathmandu|St. Xavier's]] for his [[cleft lip]]. It got so out of hand that some of the seniors stole a guitar he had borrowed from his cousin. After that incident, he left the school and joined North Point, [[Darjeeling]].\n\nAmatya enjoys [[gemology|gems]], especially regarding [[gemstone|gem]] sets containing diamonds and [[emerald]]s. He has said if he'd not been a musician, he would have been a [[jeweler]]. Amatya has a [[bachelor's degree]] in Gemology from the Gemological Institute of [[India]], [[Bombay]].\n\nAmatya is a sportsman with expertise in some sports. He has played [[association football|football]] for Army (Shreenath Gana) and NRT at center [[Striker (association football)|forward]], and has scored hat-tricks for NRT. He was declared \"[[Man of the Match]]\" in the WAVE Kick Off Cup 2006, and was one of the few who played the whole 90 minutes. Amatya is also an expert in [[tae kwon do]]. He has a Dan degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the sport, and is considered an expert in its theoretical aspects. Amatya also won medals in the sport when he was in the United States.\n\nAmatya gave his first performance at Mayur Chalchitra Mandir, [[Banepa]], while drunk. After the good response and encouragement from senior artists and friends, he started to sing for fun. He released his first album after encouragement and pestering from Brajesh Khanal and Prabhat Rimal. He dedicated the album to them and named it, in their honor, Karai Kara le.\n\nHe is fond of hunting. He is a [[pacifist]], but enjoys the thrill of the hunt. Amatya also enjoys interior designing. He took a course in interior design for 2 semesters from the School of Interior Designing in the USA.\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Compilation albums'''\n*''yogeshwor amatya jaba sandhya\n*''Bhanchan Logne Manche Bhayar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n*\n*{{cite news|url=http://jnepal.info/yogeshwor-amatya-collection/|title=yogeshwor-amatya-collection|publisher=jnepal.info|location=Nepal}}\n*\n* \n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amatya, Yogeshwar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{notability|biography|date=February 2015}}\n{{peacock|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Yogeshwar Amatya\n| image               =\n| caption             = Yogeshwar Amatya in Melancholy Song Recording at Radio Nepal Studio in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya\n| birth_place         = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| genre               = [[Soft rock]], [[pop rock]], [[folk music|folk]]\n| instrument          = Vocals guitar\n| occupation          = Singer<br> [[Composer]]<br>businessman<br> philanthropist\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Single Records|Single]] (Nepal)\n}}\n\n'''Yogeshwar Amatya''' (born Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya, 3 April) is a Nepali singer, musician, producer, actor, social activist, and photographer. Amatya has been a figure in Nepalese [[soft rock]] during the last two decades. He has sold more than 1 million records, making him one of [[List of best-selling music artists|Nepal's best-selling music artists]] and the best-selling [[Nepali rock]] artist of all time.\n\nAmatya came to fame in Nepal with his album ''Jaba Sandhya Hunchha'' and became more famous with his 1998 song ''Karai Kara Le''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nepalipopartist.blogspot.com/2007/10/yogeshwor-amatya.html | author = Thisaway | title = Profile of Nepali pop music artist..........: Yogeshwar Amatya | accessdate = 18 September 2010 | authorlink = Thisaway }}</ref> In 1998, he released his ''Ahile Chaahin Drabya Ko Aaasha Ma, Bastoo'' album which included ''Wakka Dikka''. Amatya also participated in [[Melancholy (song)|Melancholy]] song as a solo artist with 365 other Nepali singers and musician. The song set a [[Guinness World Record]] entitled \"Most Vocal Solos in a Song Recording\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-vocal-solos-in-a-song-recording|title=Most vocal solos in a song recording|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-05-29/nepali-house-hold-names-go-for-the-guinness-world-records.html|title=Nepali house-hold names go for the Guinness World Records|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/26897/|title=National poet Madhav Prasad Ghimire turns singer|first=Shreedhar|last=Pandey|website=My Republica|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYogeshwor Amatya has mentioned that he has nver received any formal training in music. He says, \"I never had any formal training regarding music... I guess I have to say that I don't have any musical background, except late night jamming with tons of beer with my buddies.\"<ref name=Telg3672213>{{cite news|url=http://www.interview.bagaicha.com/Yogeshwar-Amatya-71.html#sthash.15OZFMba.dpuf|title=Interview with Yogeshwar Amatya |author=keran limbu|publisher=bagaicha.com|date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=1 July 2011|location=Nepal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAmatya hasn't used his [[middle name]] since his father dropped it. His father, Bhuwaneshor Amatya, was the first President of Nepal Chalchitra Sangha. His mother, Lamu Amatya, was the first trained nurse in Nepal.\n\nHe was bullied by classmates while studying at [[St. Xavier's College, Kathmandu|St. Xavier's]] for his [[cleft lip]]. It got so out of hand that some of the seniors stole a guitar he had borrowed from his cousin. After that incident, he left the school and joined North Point, [[Darjeeling]].\n\nAmatya enjoys [[gemology|gems]], especially regarding [[gemstone|gem]] sets containing diamonds and [[emerald]]s. He has said if he'd not been a musician, he would have been a [[jeweler]]. Amatya has a [[bachelor's degree]] in Gemology from the Gemological Institute of [[India]], [[Bombay]].\n\nAmatya is a sportsman with expertise in some sports. He has played [[association football|football]] for Army (Shreenath Gana) and NRT at center [[Striker (association football)|forward]], and has scored hat-tricks for NRT. He was declared \"[[Man of the Match]]\" in the WAVE Kick Off Cup 2006, and was one of the few who played the whole 90 minutes. Amatya is also an expert in [[tae kwon do]]. He has a Dan degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the sport, and is considered an expert in its theoretical aspects. Amatya also won medals in the sport when he was in the United States.\n\nAmatya gave his first performance at Mayur Chalchitra Mandir, [[Banepa]], while drunk. After the good response and encouragement from senior artists and friends, he started to sing for fun. He released his first album after encouragement and pestering from Brajesh Khanal and Prabhat Rimal. He dedicated the album to them and named it, in their honor, Karai Kara le.\n\nHe is fond of hunting. He is a [[pacifist]], but enjoys the thrill of the hunt. Amatya also enjoys interior designing. He took a course in interior design for 2 semesters from the School of Interior Designing in the USA.\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Compilation albums'''\n*''yogeshwor amatya jaba sandhya\n*''Bhanchan Logne Manche Bhayar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n*\n*{{cite news|url=http://jnepal.info/yogeshwor-amatya-collection/|title=yogeshwor-amatya-collection|publisher=jnepal.info|location=Nepal}}\n*\n* \n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amatya, Yogeshwar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Sknepal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yogeshwar_Amatya"}
